article.headline: Portland holds off second-half surge
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Wesley Person gave Portland fans something to help them forget about Bonzi Wells. Person had 16 of his season-high 20 points in the second quarter when Portland outscored Minnesota 37-17 en route to 101-92 victory over the Minnesota Timberwolves on Friday night. Jeff McInnis had 21 points and eight assists for the Blazers, who snapped Minnesota's six-game winning streak. "That's all because they were aggressive and took it from us in the second quarter," said Timberwolves forward Latrell Sprewell, who had 21 points. Kevin Garnett had 27 points, 10 rebounds and nine assists to lead the Timberwolves. Sam Cassell added 23 points. Minnesota was down by as many as 18 points in the second half before pulling to 80-76 early in the fourth quarter. Person, who shot 8-of-12, then knocked in a jumper to ignite a 9-0 run. Cassell scored on a runner to pull the Timberwolves to 97-92 with 38.7 seconds remaining, but Person answered with a turnaround jumper from the top of the key with 17.5 seconds left. "No doubt Wesley changed the game," Portland coach Maurice Cheeks said. "His shooting in the second quarter was the difference." Person, a 6-foot-6 guard acquired from Memphis in Dec. 3 trade for Bonzi Wells, is averaging just 7.3 points. "This is one of those nights I got off to a good start and got into a good rhythm," he said. "The basket looked really big tonight." McInnis was 9-of-12 from the field, and matched a season-high in scoring. Rasheed Wallace had 14 points and nine rebounds for Portland, which outrebounded the Timberwolves 45-33. Garnett had 12 first-quarter points, but Wallace held him scoreless for the entire second quarter. "When you have (Michael) Olowokandi and Wally (Szczerbiak) hurt, Kevin has to do more," Minnesota coach Flip Saunders said. "He may not be scoring points, but he's rebounding, passing the ball and playing defense. We just weren't in good rhythm tonight." Portland opened the second quarter with a 10-0 run to make it 34-26. The Blazers extended their lead to 49-34 on Person's 3-pointer and Zach Randolph's short jumper. The Blazers outrebounded Minnesota 25-13 in the first half and led 61-43 at halftime. The Wolves cut their deficit to 80-72 by the end of the third. Randolph had 18 points and 12 rebounds for his 15th double-double in 27 games.

Game notes
Minnesota guard Troy Hudson (sprained ankle) sat out the game. Hudson, who started the season on the injured list, was activated Saturday and played in two games before aggravating the injury Tuesday against New York. ... The Timberwolves beat Portland 97-78 when the two teams last met April 6. Garnett had 16 points, 14 rebounds and 12 assists in that game. ...Minnesota is 11-5 on the road this season.
